		<outline text="What I Am Learning" created="Fri, 10 Apr 2020 18:58:04 GMT">
			<outline text="As much as I can about &lt;a href=&quot;https://fedwiki.frankmcpherson.net/view/welcome-visitors/view/covid-19&quot;&gt;COVID-19&lt;/a&gt; " created="Fri, 10 Apr 2020 18:58:18 GMT" collapse="true">
				<outline text="&lt;a href=&quot;https://covidactnow.org/us/michigan-mi/county/oakland_county/?s=32582081&quot;&gt;Covid ActNow&lt;/a&gt; is the site I use to track COVID data for my county and state and they recently transitioned from highlighting transmission rates like daily new cases per 100k, infection rate R(0), and positive test rate to community level metrics: weekly new cases per 100k, weekly COVID hospital admissions per 100k, percent of patients in hospital beds. The metrics align to the what the CDC is emphasizing and communicating and is a transition from focusing on spread to focusing on consequences of infection. In theory, assuming that COVID will always be with us what we are more concerned is about how many people get severe illness. I imagine this is similar to how the yearly flu is tracked. What is not clear to me is how should one react when the numbers track up in to the higher categories?" created="Wed, 20 Apr 2022 17:54:10 GMT"/>
				<outline text="Currently, &lt;a href=&quot;https://covidactnow.org/us/michigan-mi/county/oakland_county/?s=28151700&quot;&gt;66.5% of the residents in my county&lt;/a&gt; are fully vaccinated (69.6% one shot plus), which is a little better than the 60.4% for &lt;a href=&quot;https://covidactnow.org/us/michigan-mi/?s=34402239&quot;&gt;the entire state&lt;/a&gt;. Michigan is reporting that 67.2% of all residents have had at least one shot. My wife and I got our booster shot on November 16, 2021." created="Tue, 30 Mar 2021 19:37:12 GMT"/>
				<outline text="One reason to monitor new cases is the relationship between the rate of new cases and the risk of new mutations. As long as the virus spreads out of control the higher the probability of new mutations that the current vaccines don't prevent. It looks like we might have years of spring and late fall/winter outbreaks." created="Fri, 30 Apr 2021 13:16:06 GMT"/>
				<outline text="Given that it is likely we will be living with COVID-19 for many years I am expecting there will be a yearly COVID vaccine like there is for the flu. We also need to keep an eye on treatments, the more options available to doctors the better. Pfizer has developed &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pfizer.com/news/press-release/press-release-detail/pfizers-novel-covid-19-oral-antiviral-treatment-candidate&quot;&gt;an antiviral pill&lt;/a&gt; to treat COVID-19 and is seeking FDA emergency approval. Now that we approaching two full years of the pandemic we now more about treating COVID-19 than in the beginning." created="Thu, 04 Nov 2021 13:20:38 GMT"/>
				<outline text="About the Omicron variant of COVID-19" created="Mon, 13 Dec 2021 16:04:38 GMT" collapse="true">
					<outline text="New cases due to Omicron have been trending down in Michigan since mid January, 2022, and is currently at 10.2 per 100K. We are now waiting to see whether we are through the woods and can start to put COVID behind us or whether there will be another surge due to a new variant." created="Mon, 07 Mar 2022 13:32:44 GMT"/>
					<outline text="It appears as of March 7, 2022 that we are on the downside of the surge of cases caused by Omicron. " created="Mon, 07 Mar 2022 13:26:36 GMT"/>
					<outline text="We have a new variant of COVID-19 to worry about. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.webmd.com/lung/news/20211129/covid-omicron-variant-faq?src=rss_public&quot;&gt;Omicron&lt;/a&gt;. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pfizer.com/news/press-release/press-release-detail/pfizer-and-biontech-provide-update-omicron-variant&quot;&gt;Pfizer reports&lt;/a&gt; that the booster for their COVID vaccine is very effective against Omicron, and those who are fully vaccinated are well protected. Omicron is having a huge impact, case numbers and hospitalizations are at all time highs. " created="Fri, 03 Dec 2021 13:49:32 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Omicron appears to be more transmissible than Delta. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2021/12/20/what-has-omicron-changed&quot;&gt;source&lt;/a&gt; The consequence is that current at-risk people are at higher risk.  " created="Mon, 13 Dec 2021 16:06:20 GMT"/>
					<outline text="The R(t) number in the United States is 3 (similar to South Africa), with cases doubling approximately every 3 to 4 days. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2021/12/20/what-has-omicron-changed&quot;&gt;source&lt;/a&gt; " created="Mon, 13 Dec 2021 16:39:23 GMT"/>
					<outline text="Omicron has a higher reinfection rate than Delta. The COVID booster shoots increase protection against Omicron better than the base two shot regimen.  &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2021/12/20/what-has-omicron-changed&quot;&gt;source&lt;/a&gt;" created="Mon, 13 Dec 2021 16:36:50 GMT"/>
					<outline text="It appears the main concern in the United States is not that Omicron will lead to a significant increase in deaths but that it will significantly increase hospitalizations, which has corresponding consequences. The reason for the concern is the percent of the population who have not had three shots. &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.axios.com/omicron-coronavirus-cases-europe-us-c85be94d-8edf-4d61-9f05-de924bff6760.html&quot;&gt;source&lt;/a&gt;" created="Tue, 14 Dec 2021 13:51:33 GMT"/>
					</outline>
				</outline>
			<outline text="A handful of technology items has attention" created="Fri, 13 Aug 2021 17:49:23 GMT" collapse="true">
